children.subject: To add, there is the discussion of FFT in 170, and 16B does go through some DFT, but I don't think that really helps lol. Haven't taken 126 but it's really just a build-up on 70 material. 162 and 186 are about OS and Databases respectively which lean more on understanding of 61C and 61B than anything else. There is some SQL in 186 for which 61A + Data 100 (if you take it) provide exposure.
Different opinion here. Have taken 189 in fall(where math is intensive) and 127, can confirm 16B is very helpful, even crucial for many people who don't have the mathematical maturity.
Nah, not really much (or any) overlap between 16B and those courses.

history.content: Not much overlap between EE16B and any CS16x, CS17x, or CS18x (except for CS189). However, the mathematical maturity built in 16B certainly helps in classes like 126, 127, 189, since those classes assume a strong grasp of the ability to pick up new, rigorous math concepts, something 16B teaches well.

After finishing the 61 A and B as a sophomore this year, I am hoping for a SWE internship next summer, so I was planning to take CS 61C, 162,170 next school year as preparation leaving me with no more space for EE 16B.

My current plan has EE 16B in Fall senior year. So, would the material in EE 16B be helpful for CS 162, 170, 186, or EECS 126 (the classes that I want to take with and/or before)? Or is the material separate from those courses?
history.subject: EE 16B Senior Year?
